observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the City Mayor require the:
GSD and CAD to reconcile the discrepancy of P82,966,685.65 between the inventory balance per books and RPCI in accordance with  
Section 491(i)(b) of the GAAM Volume I;
GSD to submit the semestral RPCI, to the Auditor not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively in accordance with Section 124, Chapter 7, MNGAS for LGUs Volume I;
CAD to maintain SLC and SPLC for each type of supplies and other inventory items in compliance with Section 114, Chapter 7, MNGAS for LGUs Volume I and Section 4.7.2, COA Circular No. 2022-04 dated 
May 31, 2022;
GSD to use the prescribed format of ICS in accordance with Annex A.3 of COA Circular No. 2022-04 dated May 31, 2022; and
GSD to ensure the immediate issuance of Inventory Custodian Slips (ICS) to the designated end-users of all semi-expendable property in accordance with Section 3.4 of COA Circular No. 2024-006 dated 
March 14, 2024.

We recommended that the Management:
Reconcile the accounting records and the RPCPPE after the one-time cleansing of the PPE accounts;
Strictly follow the provision of COA Circular 2020-006 dated 
January 31, 2020;
Direct the GSD and CAD to fully coordinate with regards to their assignments/duties to be undertaken under the Circular; and
Submit the necessary reports to the OCA.

We recommended that Management:
Demand that the NSDRCC and APNMPC return the unexpended amount of P1,083,622.80 and remit the same to the DA;
Remit the unexpended amount of P157,000.00 to the BTr;
Utilize the P22,062,900.29 fund transfer in accordance to the MOA with SAs; and
Direct the Accountant to reclassify the amount of P30,733,651.99 from the Due to NGAs account to the Due to GOCCs account.

observations.managementAction:
The CAD had observed the provisions of NGAS Manual Volume I in the computation of depreciation. 

The CAD had prepared the required journal entry voucher in March 2024 for the noted incorrect computation of depreciation.

The CAD has already started using the delivery date as the point of initial recognition for computing the useful life of the asset.

The GSD had regularly submitted to the CAD copies of AIRs, served as basis for recording the PPE. 

Adjustments were made in April 2025 in the accounting records.

The following corrective measures are currently being implemented:

Adjustment of depreciation recognized prior to the date of acquisition;
Correction of depreciation entries to align with the month of acceptance and acquisition;
Cessation of depreciation charges on fully depreciated assets;
Uniform application of the 5% residual value, as prescribed;
Rectification of carried over errors from prior years; and
Computation of previously omitted depreciation for affected years.

observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Management:

CAD and CGSD to conduct investigation on the causes of the discrepancy and written explanations shall be required from the persons responsible;

CAD

Reconcile the PPE SLs and lapsing schedule; and

Maintain perpetual inventory records of PPELC for each category of PPE; 

GSD 

Record, monitor and account all properties, real or personal, owned by the City whether acquired through procurement or donation as provided in Section 490(b)(3)(i) of Republic Act (RA) No. 7160 – The Local Government Code of the Philippines;

We recommended that the Management:

Recalculate depreciation expense and apply the necessary adjusting journal entries to correct the accumulated depreciation recorded in the books in accordance with Paragraph 3.10, Chapter 3 of IPSAS - The Conceptual Framework for General Purpose Financial Reporting by Public Sector Entities;

Ensure that in a certain period, net book value of the assets should not be less than the residual value of five percent and make sure that only those PPE that have not reached the estimated useful life should be provided with depreciations;

Observe the correct initial recognition of depreciation expense of PPE and apply it consistently in the lapsing schedule as provided under 
IPSAS 17;

Correspond the total amount of depreciation expenses indicated in the lapsing schedule with the amount appearing in the trial balance/FS;

Provide the detailed breakdown of the lump-sum beginning balances and various adjustments made from CYs 2012 to 2021;

Reconcile the PPE SLs and Lapsing Schedule; and

Henceforth, comply strictly with Paragraphs 3.10 and 3.21, Chapter 3 of IPSAS - The Conceptual Framework for General Purpose Financial Reporting by Public Sector Entities, and IPSAS 17.

Submit the RPCI for CY 2020;

Submit the RPCI to the CAD for reconciliation and adjustment, if any; and

Direct the CAD to designate dedicated personnel who will prepare and maintain Supplies Ledger Cards (SLC) per stock to ensure that all purchases and issuances of supplies and materials are recorded in conformity with Section 120 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Vol. I.

We recommended that the Management require:
The City Accountant to coordinate with the City Treasurer in securing the pertinent documents relative to the reconciling items from the depository bank and thereafter, prepare the necessary adjustments in the books;
The City Accountant draw journal entry vouchers to record all valid reconciling items that requires adjustment and correction in the books;
The City Treasurer request the timely submission of debit/credit memos (DMs/CMs) with the depository bank; and
Henceforth, adhere to the regulations cited in COA Circular 
No. 96-011 dated October 2, 1996, relative to the reconciling items that affected the Cash in Bank accounts of the City.

We recommended that Management undertake the following courses of action:
The City Treasurer to send a written notice to the payees one month before the check becomes stale, reminding them of the existence/status of the checks and present the same if it requires replacement, as required under Section 59 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I;
Upon submission of the stale check to the City Treasurer, effect the cancellation of the same and attach the cancelled checks to the RCI for submission to the City Accountant within the period of cancellation;
The City Accountant to prepare a JEV reverting to CIB-LCA the total amount of staled cancelled checks and recognize in the books the corresponding liabilities for those stale checks that are over 6 months but not over 2 years. Also, credit the Prior Year’s Adjustment account for stale checks that are over 2 years as surplus adjustment in the Financial Statements; and
Henceforth, the Management strictly observe Section 59 of the MNGAS, Volume I and Section 97 of PD No. 1445 on the proper treatment and accounting procedures for stale and cancelled checks.

We recommended that the Management require:
The coordination between CAD and GSD to: (i) reconcile the discrepancy between accounting records and RPCPPE; and 
(ii) conduct investigation on the causes of the discrepancy and written explanations shall be required from the persons responsible;
The CAD to: (i) reconcile the PPE subsidiary ledgers and lapsing schedules and (ii) maintain perpetual inventory records of PPELC for each category of plant, property and equipment;
The GSD to exclude in the RPCPPE all semi-expendable properties and inventory items which shall properly be reported in the RPCI; and
Henceforth, strictly compliance with Section 491(i)(b) of the GAAM, Volume I, and Sections 114 and 124, Chapter 7 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I.

We recommended that Management require the City Accountant to:
Apply the effect of change in accounting estimate prospectively in accounting records in compliance with Paragraphs 7 and 41 of 
IPSAS 3 and Item 7.3(d)(2) of COA Circular No. 2017-004;
Observe the correct initial recognition of depreciation expense for PPE and apply it consistently in the lapsing schedule as provided under 
PAG 3 of IPSAS 17;
Ensure that in a certain period, net book value of the assets should not be less than the residual value of 5 percent;
Ensure that only those PPEs that have not reached the estimated useful life should be provided with depreciation;
Correspond the total amount of depreciation expenses indicated in the lapsing schedule with the amount appearing in the trial balance/financial statements;
Provide the detailed breakdown of the lump-sum beginning balances and various adjustments made from CYs 2017-2021; and
Henceforth, comply strictly with Paragraphs 7 and 41 of IPSAS 3 – Accounting Policies, Changes in Accounting Estimate and Errors, Philippine Application Guidance 3 to IPSAS 17, and Item 7.3(d)(2) of COA Circular No. 2017-004.

We recommended that the Management:
Require coordination between the City Health Department, GSD and CAD to facilitate the provision of all related documents on donations for the timely recording/reporting of the same;
Require the City Accountant to: (i) Prepare the necessary adjusting entries to correct the recording of the issued medical supplies and COVID-19 vaccines received through donations by the Management in compliance with Paragraph IV(C)(7) of COA Circular No. 2014-002 dated April 15, 2014; and (ii) Record the receipt of donated ambulances amounting to P14,628,000.00 in the books under Motor Vehicle account, adjust the recorded Medical Equipment by P2,580,413.24 and derecognize the Grants and Donations in Kind account and instead record the receipt of donated PPEs under Government Equity account as prescribed in Paragraph IV(C)(4) of COA Circular No. 2014-002 dated April 15, 2014;
The GSD should properly record, monitor and account all properties, real or personal, owned by the City whether acquired through procurement or donation as provided in Section 490(b)(3)(i) of RA 
No. 7160 – The Local Government Code of the Philippines; and
Henceforth, comply strictly with Paragraph IV(C)(4) and (7) of COA Circular No. 2014-002 dated April 15, 2014, and Section 490(b)(3)(i) of RA No. 7160 for the proper accounting treatment and accountability of donation received by the City.

We recommended that the Management require the CAD to:
Record the receipt of purchased Inventories using the Perpetual Inventory Method and expense the same once the goods are distributed in line with Section 114 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I, and Paragraph 44 of IPSAS 12 - Inventories;
Maintain the SLC for each commodity/stock to guarantee proper reconciliation of records with the GSD in compliance with Section 114 and 120 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I;
Apply the Moving Average Method as the basis of computation in determining the cost of inventories in accordance with Section 115 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I; and
Henceforth, comply strictly with Sections 114, 115, and 120 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I, and Paragraph 44 of 
IPSAS 12 - Inventories.

We recommended that Management require the LCPC through the CSWDD to:
Ensure the appropriation of 1 percent of its IRA in the City’s annual budget for the implementation of PPAs of the LCPC pursuant to RA No. 9344 and DILG MC No. 2012-120;
Prepare and approve the required plans and reports to strengthen the intervention, monitoring, and evaluation of related LCPC’s PPAs and included the said activities in the Annual Investment Plan;
Ascertain that only LCPC PPAs are allowed to be programmed, funded, and included in the Annual Investment Plan of the 1 percent IRA as required under Rule 21 of IRR of RA No.  9344, as amended by RA No. 10630, and Item II of DILG MC No. 2012-120; and
Henceforth, strictly comply with the relevant provisions of the IRR of RA No. 9344, as amended by RA No. 10630 and DILG MC No. 2012-120 in the appropriation, utilization, preparation of plans and reports, monitoring, and evaluation relative to the 1 percent IRA for LCPC.

We recommended that Management required the CAD to:
Revert back immediately the amount of P3,185,307.08 to the unappropriated surplus of the GF pursuant to Item 5.1.13 of COA Circular No. 2012-02 dated September 12, 2012;
Clarify and provide explanation on the noted amount transferred to TF from the unexpended balance of the DRRM fund of CYs 2011 to 2014 exceeding by P3,730,921.74 as compared with the LDRRMFIP;
Ensure that all implemented LDRRMF PPAs are budgeted and included in the LDRRMFIP; and
Henceforth, strictly comply with Item 5.1.13 of COA Circular 
No. 2012-02 on the proper treatment of unutilized LDRRMF that had exceeded the five-year validity period.

We recommended that Management require:
The CHRMDD to immediately coordinate with the GSIS for the reconciliation of employee information to facilitate the remittance of the P1,389,136.69 representing prior years’ contributions;
Immediately remit the amount of P2,049,161.58, net of the amount left unremitted due to discrepancies of employees’ information to avoid unnecessary incurrence of interest and penalties;
The CTD to assign a dedicated personnel that will closely coordinate with CAD for the processing of disbursement vouchers to facilitate timely remittance of monthly contributions and loan amortization; and
The prompt and full remittance of withheld contributions and loan amortizations pursuant to Sections 14, 15 and 16 of the IRR of RA 
No. 8291, moving forward.

The City Treasurer’s Department (CTD) to submit supporting documents, records or communications covering CYs 1999 to 2003 for the P31.616 million unrecorded disbursements and unidentified reconciling items to the City Accounting for recording in the books of accounts;

The City Accounting Department (CAD) to expedite the submission of 13 bank reconciliation statements (BRS) for the noted discrepancy of P9.448 million; and

Henceforth, submit on time the complete BRS with bank statements for all the bank accounts maintained by the City to the Office of the City Auditor.

Reconcile the discrepancy between the books and RPCPPE;

Reconcile the General Ledgers (GL) and Subsidiary Ledgers (SL) of PPE accounts;

Designate dedicated personnel to ensure all PPE items have corresponding property cards and guarantee the up-to-date information indicated therein for easy reconciliation with CAD’s accounting records;

Designate dedicated personnel who will maintain PPE Ledger Cards for each category of assets and Real Property Ledger Cards for land in accordance with Section 120 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Vol. I; and

Prospectively, apply any change in accounting estimate in accordance with International Public Sector Accounting Standard (IPSAS) 3, observe the correct initial recognition of depreciation expense for PPE as stated in Philippine Application Guidance (PAG) 3 of IPSAS 17, and ensure the accuracy on the computation of depreciation expense.

Inform the respective accountable officers to return the unserviceable PPEs to GSD for cancellation of Memorandum Receipt /Acknowledgment Receipt of Equipment for proper accountability;

Process the immediate disposal of the unserviceable assets amounting to P3,563,739.00 in accordance with Section 167 of COA Circular No. 92-386;

Direct the CAD to reflect the necessary adjustment/ derecognition to the balances of PPE account upon disposal of the said PPEs; and

Henceforth, strictly comply with Section 167 of COA Circular No. 92-386 for subsequent disposal of unserviceable PPEs.

Submit the lacking documents enumerated in Paragraphs 7.6, 7.8, and 7.11 to this Office for verification and audit;
Submit explanation/ justification on how the suppliers were able to provide their quotation even without basis (Paragraph 7.6);
Stop processing of payments without complete supporting documents; and
Remit immediately the P180,000.00 representing the 2 and 3 percent Expanded Withholding Tax and Percentage Taxes due to BIR (Paragraph 7.9).

We recommended that:
The City Treasurer –
Coordinate with the depository banks as regards the documents to support the unadjusted and unidentified reconciling items under the GF;
Upon receipt of the monthly Bank Reconciliation Statements, check the completeness of the DM/CMs and other documents and immediately inform the bank/s of any missing items;
The City Accountant –
Assign personnel to prepare the bank reconciliation statements on a monthly basis for all depository accounts pursuant to COA Circular No. 96-011;
Submit bank reconciliation statements for all the bank accounts maintained by the City to the Office of the City Auditor; and
Effect immediately adjusting entries in the books of accounts for all reconciling items identified in the BRS.

We recommended that the CTD thru BTMD:
Strictly implement and enforce the provisions of Section 2H.06 (a-d) of City Ordinance No. A10-2016;
Impose and collect immediately the ten percent (10%) amusement tax on admission on cockpits for the past five years;
Require the owners and/or operators of movie houses and cockpits to register their admission tickets as required in Section 2H.06 (c) of City Ordinance No. A10-2016 and record the serial numbers in the logbook for control purposes; and
Create a monitoring unit and assign competent personnel to conduct validation of receipts, and periodic inspections as required in Section 2H.06 (d) of the Ordinance.

We recommended that:
The CHRM Officer prepare a list, together with the City Health Officer (CHO) for PHWs and City Social Welfare and Development Officer (CSWDO), for PSWs that meet the requirements, for entitlement to Hazard Pay, and Subsistence Allowance pursuant to DBM and DOH Joint Circular No. 1, S. 2016 and DBM and DSWD Joint Circular No. 1, S. 2018;
The LCE review the list of PHWs and have it approved by the Secretary of Health;
The CSWDO review the list of PSWs and have it approved by the LCE;
The CHO and CSWDO prepare the pertinent lists of employees and certify that they are required to make their services available at any and all times;
The CAD to –
Require the refund of Hazard Pay, Subsistence Allowance and Laundry Allowance paid to those employees who did not meet the requirements under the above-mentioned Joint Circulars; and
Require the refund of P7,446.40 Laundry Allowance from CSWDD employees and stop the payment of the same.

We reiterated last year’s recommendations that: 

The CGSD and the Inventory Committee complete the reconciliation of the RPCPPE with the CAD and CGSD records;

The CAD –

Effect the necessary adjustments to correct the balances of the PPE accounts based on the results of the reconciliation made;

Reclassify items costing below P10,000.00 to the appropriate semi-expendable accounts; and

The CGSD cause the immediate disposal of unserviceable items and the CAD to record the dropping from the books of the items disposed.

We recommended that the  Accountant:

Review, analyze and trace back the transactions that caused the negative balances and prepare the adjusting entries to correct the affected accounts;

Make arrangement with the BIR for the immediate recovery of the over remittances since under the Revenue Code, claim for refund of overpaid taxes must be filed within the 2-year prescriptive period from the time the right of claim accrues;




Exert  effort to collect the overpayment of salary from concerned employees; and

The City Treasurer coordinate with the depository banks as regards to the documents to support the unadjusted and unidentified reconciling items under the General Fund;



The City Mayor through the CLD demand justification/ information from the City Treasurer on the unjustified delay in the submission of disbursement vouchers which are not supported with documents; 



The City Accountant:

Assign personnel to prepare the BRS on a monthly basis for all depository accounts pursuant to COA Circular No. 96-011; and



Effect adjusting entries immediately in the books of accounts for reconciling items already identified.

The City Assessor –

Maintain and keep an updated record of all idle lands located within the City of Malabon; 



Furnish the Office of the City Treasurer with an updated record of idle lands for imposition of additional tax in accordance with Section 239 of RA 7160 and Section 2B.06, Article B of City Ordinance No. A10-2016;

The City Treasurer –

Send notice of assessment to all owners of idle lands in the City; and

Impose and collect ad valorem tax on all idle lands in the City.

The City Treasurer remit immediately to the BIR, GSIS, and Pag-IBIG the unremitted taxes, contributions and loan payments;

 The Management –

Exert efforts to recover the amount due to over/ double remittances to different NGA/ GOCCs and overpayment of employees’ salaries;

Identify the person who caused the over/double remittance or overpayment and make him/her accountable therefor;



The CAD –

Institute appropriate measures to minimize if not eliminate the occurrence of over/double remittances; and

Submit status of action taken, for recovery from BIR the double remittances of VAT for May 2016 thru e-filling totalling P197,966.39, otherwise, make adjusting entry/s for Due from BIR to Due from Officers and employees to recognize accountability of personnel who caused the double remittance.

Review, analyze and trace back the transactions that caused the negative balances and prepare the adjusting entries to correct the affected accounts;

Make arrangement with the BIR for the immediate recovery of the over remittances since under the Revenue Code, claim for refund of overpaid taxes must be filed within the 2-year prescriptive period from the time the right of claim accrues;



Exert  effort to collect the overpayment of salary from concerned employees; and

The City’s LDRRM Council include in the LDRRMF Plan the following:

Construction of permanent warehouse/storage facilities located in accessible, safe and secured areas with shelves or cabinet to avoid possible damage/spoilage and/or loss/pilferage of relief goods and materials;



Relief Distribution Mechanism to serve as a guide in the distribution and disposal of supplies, materials and relief goods to calamity victims; 

The City Mayor designate a warehouse keeper to discharge the functions and responsibilities for the safekeeping and issuances of relief goods; 

The designated warehouse keeper limit access to warehouses/storage facilities to authorized personnel and releases the relief goods/construction materials directly to the calamity victims/intended beneficiaries based on validated list of calamity affected families; and

The designated personnel maintain updated records on the receipt and issuance of supplies and materials and maintain a stock card for each item of construction materials and other supplies for purposes of monitoring the balance 
and availability of stocks/items on hand.

Examine the validity and actual existence of the receivables account which remained dormant for 5 to 33 years already; 



Make the necessary adjustment/s in the books, if warranted, to reflect the actual and correct account balance of Other Receivables account; and

Revisit the MOA or loan agreement on micro lending and institute procedures to collect the loan.

We recommended that:
The City Treasurer remit immediately to the BIR, GSIS, and Pag-IBIG the unremitted taxes, contributions and loan payments;
Management -
Exert efforts to recover the amount due to over/double remittances to different NGA/GOCCs and overpayment of employees’ salaries;
Identify the person who caused the over/double remittance or overpayment and make him/her accountable therefor;
The City Accounting Department -
Institute appropriate measures to minimize if not eliminate the occurrence of over/double remittances; and
Submit status of action taken, for recovery from BIR the double remittances of VAT for May 2016 thru e-filling totaling P197,966.39, otherwise, make adjusting entry/s for Due from BIR to Due from Officers and Employees to recognize accountability of personnel who caused the double remittance.

We recommended that the Accountant:
review, analyze and trace back the transactions that caused the negative balances and prepare the adjusting entries to correct the affected accounts;
make arrangement with the BIR for the immediate recovery of the over remittances since under the Revenue Code, claim for refund of overpaid taxes must be filed within the 2-year prescriptive period from the time the right of claim accrues;
exert  effort to collect the overpayment of salary from concerned employees; and
reassess existing internal control measures to identify the cause/s of the recurring negative balances.

